chanisms for a developer to present to council prior to going to an appeal\nprocess. ","index":"01406","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWiebe:</b> So again, if the minister can just lay out exactly what steps a\ndeveloper would have to take before they got to the appeal process. ","index":"01407","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> That is a long drawn-out step. As you heard here from the\npresenters tonight, that some of them have been years in the process of going\nthrough this before the appeal process. ","index":"01408","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWiebe:</b> So, you're saying they would still need to go through those years of\nappeals or years of process before they got to the appeal process? What does it\nmatter changing it from 30 to 14 days then? ","index":"01409","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> And this was a requirement that the AMM brought forward because\nthey want closure at the end of their decision, to know if it will be appealed\nthey would want to know sooner than later. So this is an amendment that was\nsuggested by AMM and we support them in this amendment. ","index":"01410","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWiebe:</b> So, again, I think the minister needs to be a little bit more clear\nabout exactly the steps that a developer would have to take.","index":"01411","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� I\nguess the concern that, of course, we have, in addition to many others with\nregards to how this is going to play out. We've heard from the CAOs and some of\nthe concerns they've had, is that this potentially favours those developers who\nwould have the resources, have the knowledge, be able to meet that 14-day\nrequirement. ","index":"01412","speaker":""},{"html":"����� What\nsorts of provisions are there for the average citizen to make representation to\nhave a development reconsidered? ","index":"01413","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> Yes, as stated earlier, the citizens can present at Municipal\nBoard, they have that right as well, along with other AMM�or other\nrepresents�representatives of the municipality; the public, in general, they\ncan participate in the appeal process. ","index":"01414","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWiebe:</b> But now they only have the 14 days. So, I guess that's where my\nconcern comes in.","index":"01415","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� If you\nare a developer, you would have all the resources and the ability to meet that\nrequirement. If you're an average person, you maybe don't have the same\nresources. ","index":"01416","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So,\nyou're saying the only place that they can go&nbsp;is the Municipal Board and\nthat will now be only 14 days to make that appeal? ","index":"01417","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> No, that's not accurate. Through the whole planning process, the\npublic has the right to present for all the decision-making opportunities that\nthe municipality puts forward through planning, and those opportunities are\nthere, but they're also there at the Municipal Board.","index":"01418","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWiebe:</b> And at the Municipal Board, then, for individuals who�or, I guess,\ndevelopers who want to bring forward�what are the steps exactly that they would\nhave to go through? ","index":"01419","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� I'm\njust concerned about this where you're saying it's, you know, well, they have\nall these�there's provisions in the bill that would bring these parties\ntogether to work something out. Exactly how would that process work? ","index":"01420","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> This is if all other provisions fail, the�they have to apply\nwithin 14 days to appeal the decision. So the hearing isn't in 14 days, the\napplication to appeal would be within 14 days. And as I said, the\nmunicipalities, AMM, have proposed this so they can get closure on their\ndecision. ","index":"01421","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWiebe:</b> Okay, I think I understand this. What I guess I'm trying to get at\nis exactly, at the Municipal Board, what is the process to avoid it from being\nappealed? ","index":"01422","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� So,\nyou had talked about provisions that they�the parties have to go through to\nensure that it doesn't get appealed. We've heard concerns all night from\nmunicipalities who are saying that there's going to be a rush to appeal because\nit's not set out in the legislation exactly what is necessary to trigger an appeal.\n","index":"01423","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So if the decision goes the\nwrong way, what's to stop anybody from appealing immediately? And then, you\nknow, 14 days, 30 days, 90 days, doesn't matter, it's still got to go through\nthat process and potentially overwhelm that appeal process. ","index":"01424","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Johnson:</b> As mentioned,\nwe've increased the budget for the Municipal Board 42 per cent this year and in\nbudget '21-22 so they'll have the resources to listen to the appeals. ","index":"01425","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Wiebe:</b> Well, you know, I\nalso heard the minister say tonight that he has a backlog that he's still\nworking on after five years of being an elected official. So, I mean, it just,\nyou know�I guess we can all just hope and pray that they're going to figure\nthis out and maybe throw a couple extra bucks at it. It might clear out or be able\nto handle the increased workload.","index":"01426","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� But, you know, it still\ndoesn't address the issue that AMM and every other elected official brought\nhere tonight that this is an appeal first and�appeal-first process, which is\nnot helpful to anybody. ","index":"01427","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So I appreciate that we're\ntaking baby steps. Maybe the minister has some secret amendments that he's\ngoing to pull out of his back pocket at the last second here that will make it\na little better. I see him flashing some papers over there. So hopefully it'll\naddress some of these other concerns.","index":"01428","speaker":""},{"html":"����� But I'm just, you know, I\nmean, this doesn't seem to get at the heart of the issue that we've heard from\npresenters here tonight. ","index":"01429","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thanks\nvery much, Mr. Chair. ","index":"01430","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> All right.","index":"01431","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Is the\ncommittee ready for the question on this amendment? ","index":"01432","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Question. ","index":"01433","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I'm about to read the question for the committee, but I\nwill�I'll advise you that you are allowed to dispense this particular reading.","index":"01434","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> Dispense. ","index":"01435","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Dispense.","index":"01436","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Amendment�pass;\nclause 22 as amended�pass; clause 23�pass.","index":"01437","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 24 through 26 pass? ","index":"01438","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"01439","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"01440","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 24 pass? ","index":"01441","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"01442","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> No.","index":"01443","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Johnson:</b>\nWe would like this removed. ","index":"01444","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Okay. ","index":"01445","speaker":""},{"html":"����� All\nthose in favour�oh, so I don't have to say that. I can just say clause 24 is\naccordingly defeated. And that's it. ","index":"01446","speaker":""},