,"speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> We're changing the regulation-making authority from major\noccupancy to major development. ","index":"01482","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nWiebe:</b> Maybe I'll give the minister just a second to get some clarity and\njust want to get a definition of the word, in the case of the bill, what was\noriginally meant by occupancy. ","index":"01483","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� And there's no rush to answer. ","index":"01484","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Johnson:</b> It's�changing the\nregulation-making authority from major occupancy to major develop�ment will\nallow greater flexibility to place limits and define this new power to ensure\nit is used appropriately by the municipalities. ","index":"01485","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Wiebe:</b> Okay. We might need a\nlittle bit of a reboot of the minister here, as�shut the system down and\nrestart. ","index":"01486","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� But it looks like maybe officials\nare jotting down some notes and might just help clarify for all of us. ","index":"01487","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Johnson:</b> Occupancy is a term\ngenerally used for building codes. Major development is more clear in the\ndevelopment planning process. ","index":"01488","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Wiebe:</b> Well, you now, maybe I\nwon't belabour the point because maybe we can ask this offline, but I guess I'm\njust a little bit perplexed why occupancy would have been used in the original\nlegislation, because it sounds like development was the original intent. ","index":"01489","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Johnson:</b> Yes, occupancy is a\nterm generally used for building codes and in this case, major development is\nmore clear in the development process�in the planning process. ","index":"01490","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Wiebe:</b> I'll leave it at that,\nMr. Chair. ","index":"01491","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Oh, I appreciate\nthat so much. ","index":"01492","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Any other members wish to comment?\nGood.","index":"01493","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So, the amendment is still fresh\nin our minds. ","index":"01494","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Amendment�pass;\nclause 38 as amended�pass. ","index":"01495","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall clause 39 pass? ","index":"01496","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some Honourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"01497","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Johnson:</b> I move","index":"01498","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<i>THAT Clause 39 of the Bill be amended\nin the proposed subsection 151.0.3(3) by striking out</i> <i>\"</i>30&nbsp;days<i>\"</i>\n<i>wherever</i> <i>it occurs and substituting�</i>it with<i>�\"</i>14 days<i>\".\n</i>","index":"01499","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Apparently, I misread that, so I\nwill re-read it. So, I move ","index":"01500","speaker":""},{"html":"<i>THAT Clause 39 of the Bill be amended\nin the proposed subsection 151.0.3(3) by striking out \"</i>30&nbsp;days<i>\"\nwherever it occurs and substituting \"</i>14&nbsp;days<i>\". </i>","index":"01501","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><i>Motion\npresented.</i></b> ","index":"01502","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> The amendment is in order. ","index":"01503","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The floor is open for questions. ","index":"01504","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Johnson:</b> I think we've\ndiscussed this. It's a proposal brought forward by AMM, and we support it.� ","index":"01505","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Wiebe:</b> Well, I�you know,\nmaybe I'll just put a quick word on the record, because I don't know how many\namendments the minister is bringing. I think this speaks to, as I said earlier,\njust how half-baked this legislation is that here we are, trying to amend it.","index":"01506","speaker":"Matt Wiebe"},{"html":"����� My concern remains that we are\nmaking very sma